BEIJING December 5 (Xinhua) Chinese scientists believe that global warming particularly higher winter temperatures will continue to the first half of the 21st century.
In a key research project underway since the early 1990s nearly 100 scientists in China have concluded that the average global temperature has risen about 0.
The scientists led by Ye Duzheng an aerophysicist and academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences said that the increase rate of gases that cause the greenhouse effect will accelerate so much so that the earth s warming trend will continue in the coming dozens of years.
Affected by natural changes and human activities the average winter temperature in northern China by the year 2030 will be 1 to 1.
5 degrees Centigrade higher than the present figure according to the scientists.
On the other hand the increase rate of summer temperatures will be lower than that in winter.
The scientists said that the warming effect especially rising temperatures in winter will result in a series of changes to nature and human society.
The production of wheat will rise while corn will yield a lower overall volume.
Global Warming Affecting Antarctic Ice Sheet.
CANBERRA May 27 (Xinhua) Sea levels would rise as the Antarctic ice sheet melted because of higher temperatures caused by global warming Australian geologists said Wednesday.
New England University s Barrie McKelvey said a recent Australian National Antarctic Research Expedition found evidences that the ice sheet was considerably smaller during the last major period of global warming 3 8 million years ago.
He said the discovery of remnants of river and lake sediment was a major step in supporting the assertion that global warming would lead to a rise in world sea levels.
McKelvey told the Australian Associated Press in Sydney.
He said researchers found preserved elements of the landscape predating the Antarctic ice sheet and strata from fossil valleys created by lakes and rivers but the materials still need to be examined.
McKelvey said the team s ultimate aim was to show the likely effect of future global warming.
The ice sheet currently contains 27 million cubic kilometers of water which if released would cause a 65 meter rise in world sea levels.
It would also result in climate change caused by the alteration in deep sea water currents and temperatures and a decrease in the amount of solar heat reflected by ice into the atmosphere.
